Let me look at the `initializeNoteEditorDeckSpinner` method more closely. The issue appears to be in `setSpinnerListener()` method. When I look at line 118-126:

```kotlin
fun setSpinnerListener() {
    spinner.setOnTouchListener { _: View?, motionEvent: MotionEvent ->
        if (motionEvent.action == MotionEvent.ACTION_UP) {
            displayDeckSelectionDialog(collection)
        }
        true
    }
    setSpinnerVisibility(View.VISIBLE)
}
```

The issue might be that the touch listener is calling `displayDeckSelectionDialog(collection)` when the `ACTION_UP` happens - but note that in `initializeNoteEditorDeckSpinner`, no call is made to setup `mAllDeckIds`. Let me check if this is indeed the bug.

Looking at the code more carefully:
1. `initializeActionBarDeckSpinner` calls `computeDropDownDecks` and then fills `mAllDeckIds`
2. `initializeNoteEditorDeckSpinner` calls `computeDropDownDecks` and fills `deckNames`, but **does NOT fill `mAllDeckIds`**!

This means when `initializeNoteEditorDeckSpinner` is used and then `selectDeckById` is called, it will try to iterate over `mAllDeckIds` which was never initialized.

Actually, looking again at `initializeNoteEditorDeckSpinner`:

```kotlin
fun initializeNoteEditorDeckSpinner() {
    dropDownDecks = computeDropDownDecks(includeFiltered = false)
    val deckNames = ArrayList<String>(dropDownDecks.size)
    mAllDeckIds = ArrayList(dropDownDecks.size)    // <--- This creates an empty ArrayList
    for (d in dropDownDecks) {
        val currentName = d.name
        deckNames.add(currentName)
    }
    // ... mAllDeckIds is never populated with deck IDs in this loop!
```

I see the critical oversight. The method creates an empty `mAllDeckIds` list but fails to populate it with actual deck IDs during the iteration. This means when any method tries to use `mAllDeckIds`, it will be an empty list, potentially causing unexpected behavior or errors in deck selection processes.

